SIMPLE: toss
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Toss
<hw>Toss</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tossed</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; (less properly
<conjf>Tost</conjf> ); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tossing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[ W. <ets>tosiaw</ets>,
<ets>tosio</ets>, to jerk, toss, snatch, <ets>tos</ets>a quick jerk, a
toss, a snatch. ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw with the hand;
especially, to throw with the palm of the hand upward, or to throw
upward; <as>as, to <ex>toss</ex> a ball</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lift or throw up with a sudden or violent motion;
<as>as, to <ex>toss</ex> the head</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>tossed</qex> his arm aloft, and proudly told me,⟦br⟧
He would not stay.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to rise and fall; <as>as, a ship
<ex>tossed</ex> on the waves in a storm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We being exceedingly <qex>tossed</qex> with a tempest.</q>
<rj><qau>Act xxvii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To agitate; to make restless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Calm region once,⟦br⟧
And full of peace, now <qex>tossed</qex> and turbulent.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Hence, to try; to harass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whom devils fly, thus is he <qex>tossed</qex> of men.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To keep in play; to tumble over; <as>as, to spend
four years in <ex>tossing</ex> the rules of grammar</as>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Ascham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To toss off</b></col>, <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>to drink
hastily.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>to accomplish easily or quickly.</cd>
<sd>(c)</sd> <cd>to say in an offhand manner; <as>as, to <ex>toss
off</ex> a comment</as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>to masturbate; -- British
slang.</cd> -- <col><b>To toss the cars</b></col>.<cd>See under Oar,
<pos>n.</pos></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Toss
<hw>Toss</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To roll and tumble; to
be in violent commotion; to write; to fling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>toss</qex> and fling, and to be restless, only frets and
enrages our pain.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be tossed, as a fleet on the ocean.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To toss for</b></col>, <cd>to throw dice or a coin to
determine the possession of; to gamble for.</cd> -- <col><b>To toss
up</b></col>, <cd>to throw a coin into the air, and wager on which side
it will fall, or determine a question by its fall.</cd>
<au>Bramsion.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Toss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Toss
<hw>Toss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A throwing upward, or with
a jerk; the act of tossing; <as>as, the <ex>toss</ex> of a
ball</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A throwing up of the head; a particular manner of
raising the head with a jerk.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tossel</ent>⟦br⟧
